{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476220"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:43:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:43:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13705"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13705"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.16,0.28,0.05,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49041"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6321"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34068"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2756"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11142"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18317"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18458"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44162"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49041"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parents with a one-month history of headaches, leg pain after moderate activity, and fatigue. She used to be active in school sports but now avoids physical activity. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her family history is unremarkable. On examination, she appears well. Her right arm blood pressure is 140/90 mmHg and leg blood pressure is 100/70 mmHg. A systolic ejection murmur is heard best at the left infraclavicular area and radiates to the back. Femoral pulses are weak. A chest X-ray reveals rib notching and cardiomegaly. An echocardiogram shows narrowing of the aorta just distal to the left subclavian artery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most serious complication this patient is at risk for if left untreated?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right heart failure","Paradoxical embolism","Intracranial haemorrhage","Pulmonary embolism","Renal failure"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario describes a patient with signs and symptoms consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoarctation of the aorta\u003C/strong\u003E, including differential blood pressure between the upper and lower extremities, systolic murmur, rib notching, and cardiomegaly. Coarctation of the aorta can lead to several complications if left untreated, but \u003Cstrong\u003Eintracranial haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E is the most serious and potentially life-threatening complication. It happens due to the increased pressure proximal to the coarctation, leading to increased cerebral arterial pressure. The increased blood pressure in the cerebral vessels can cause the formation of berry aneurysms, which have a high risk of rupture, resulting in a subarachnoid or intracerebral haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight heart failure\u003C/strong\u003E can occur due to increased afterload from left ventricular outflow obstruction, leading to left ventricular hypertrophy and eventually left-sided heart failure. Although right-sided heart failure may follow left-sided heart failure, the immediate concern in this patient is the risk of intracranial haemorrhage due to severe hypertension, making right heart failure a less immediate threat.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParadoxical embolism\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when a venous thrombus crosses into the arterial system through a right-to-left shunt, such as a patent foramen ovale. Aortic coarctation does not typically cause conditions that lead to paradoxical embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically arises from thrombi in the deep veins of the legs or pelvis and is not directly associated with aortic coarctation. The pathophysiology of coarctation primarily involves increased upper body blood pressure, leading to risks like intracranial haemorrhage rather than pulmonary embolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal failure\u003C/strong\u003E can result from prolonged severe hypertension, leading to hypertensive nephropathy. Although this is a significant concern in chronic hypertension, it is not the most immediate risk associated with untreated aortic coarctation. The patient\u0027s differential blood pressure and signs of severe hypertension place her at greater immediate risk for intracranial haemorrhage due to the formation of aneurysms and potential for rupture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Untreated aortic coarctation significantly increases the risk of intracranial haemorrhage.","Early diagnosis and timely surgical intervention are critical to prevent serious complications.","Rib notching on chest X-ray is a key diagnostic feature of aortic coarctation."],"references":["Andrade L, Hoskoppal A, Martin MH, Whitehead K, Ou Z, Kuang J, Cox D. Intracranial aneurysm and coarctation of the aorta: prevalence in the current era. Cardiology in the Young. 2021 Feb;31(2):229-32.https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/cardiology-in-the-young/article/abs/intracranial-aneurysm-and-coarctation-of-the-aorta-prevalence-in-the-current-era/37164DFFD9D83781E598A108A3F3871E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34068"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13705"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34068"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-22T21:03:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-02T20:00:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6321"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49041"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"